metaData.descriptionCS: The child copies symbols that are paired with simple geometric shapes or numbers. Using a key, the child draws each symbol in its corresponding shape or box within a specified time limit.

questions.title: A: Demo & Sample Items
questions.correctInstructionsHTML:
Correct response:

Offer praise such as Yes or Right, and finally, Now you know how to do them.
questions.incorrectInstructionsHTML:
Incorrect response:

If the child makes a mistake on a sample item, correct the error immediately. Use the item to review use of the key. Continue to help the child, if necessary, until the child correctly completes the sample items. Use explanations such as This is a square. The square has this mark (point to square in key), so you should draw the same mark here (point to empty square).

Do not proceed with the test items until the child has correctly completed the sample items and understands the task. If it is clear that the child will not understand the task with further instruction, use the pencil icon to add a note saying the child did not understand the task. Enter 0 for the total correct score for the subtest. Refer to the Invalidating Subtest Scores section in Chapter 2 of the WISC–V Administration and Scoring Manual for more information.

When the child has successfully completed the sample items, proceed to Test Items.
questions.topInstructionsHTML:
Say, Now you do these (point to sample items). Stop when you get to this line (point to heavy line that separates sample items from test items). Hand the child a #2 pencil without an eraser and say, Go ahead. Allow the child to complete the sample items.

If a left-handed child partially blocks the key with his or her left hand while completing the sample items, stop administration. Place an extra Response Booklet to the right of the child’s Response Booklet so the extra key is aligned with the key in the child’s Response Booklet. Have the child complete the remaining sample items, using the extra key, so he or she will be accustomed to the arrangement when completing the test items.
